The European Green Deal
NEW YORK – She did it.
The "green deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is so far the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It therefore becomes a reference point for the entire world – a guide for the transition to a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, the first agenda, for everyone's use, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting the Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents just made public reveals this: an apparent abundance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of related and interconnected subjects ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined based on objectives subject to a timeline, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Globally, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to put in place a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor kill the land with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Once again, critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere window dressing for pipe dreams.
But go talk to useless chatter about French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced over a year of protests turning into riots, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted in unrest this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately seeking how to organize or structure a public consultation, but afterwards.
American neoliberal supporters will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But one need only look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Stepping into an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, escalators, broken shuttle buses, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that you can't drive on them, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each U.S. election cycle now costs up to $8 billion, and the funding is ensured by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions provided by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows a government as it should be and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not strictly partisan).
A mixed economy, combining markets, the regulatory power of the state, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investment in infrastructure, private investment in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad strokes, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy, already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and the collaborative economy in transport or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flow of primary resources.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public aids.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like other regions of the world as is well known, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, from 1% to 2%, toward the green economy, particularly in the areas of new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Financing will come from the private sector as well as public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for approximately 9.1 % of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share reaches 30 % and that of the United States reaches 14 %.
Even if Europe manages to implement its Green Deal in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest emitter of CO2 (although its per capita emissions remain half of those of the United States).
China, alone, will determine the future of global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risk diplomatic isolation if they do not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the ill-fated cold war launched by America.
The hardline proponents within the government and the Chinese coal lobbies resist, under pressure from the United States, decarbonization, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to the insidious measures of America to hinder China and instead proposes to this latter country a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together on the establishment of infrastructure, development, and sustainable technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen of Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
